1. Obtaining Data

The dataset used for this analysis was sourced from Kaggle through the following link: Bank Account Fraud Dataset. Kaggle is a well-known platform that provides a wide range of datasets for data analysis, machine learning, and research.

The dataset, titled Bank Account Fraud Dataset (NeurIPS 2022), is part of the NeurIPS 2022 competition and is focused on the detection of fraudulent activities associated with bank accounts.

Data Collection Process Source: The data was downloaded directly from the Kaggle website. The dataset is publicly available, meaning anyone can access it. Collection Method: The dataset was manually downloaded in CSV format after accessing the public page on Kaggle. Tools Used: The data was downloaded manually using a web browser and imported into the analysis environment ( R Lab ) for further exploration and analysis.

Summary of Data Source and Collection Source: Kaggle, Bank Account Fraud Dataset (NeurIPS 2022). Type of Data: Pre-processed CSV files that are ready for analysis. Collection Process: Manual download from Kaggle. Purpose: The dataset is structured to help detect fraudulent activities in bank accounts, making it a suitable candidate for machine learning models focused on fraud detection.

A more detailed explanation of the data collection process, including the file structure and preliminary data exploration, can be found in the sections below.

Dictionary

  • income (numeric): Annual income of the applicant (in decile form). Ranges between [0.1, 0.9].
  • name_email_similarity (numeric): Metric of similarity between email and applicant’s name. Higher values represent higher similarity. Ranges between [0, 1].
  • prev_address_months_count (numeric): Number of months in previous registered address of the applicant, i.e. the applicant’s previous residence, if applicable. Ranges between [−1, 380] months (-1 is a missing value).
  • current_address_months_count (numeric): Months in currently registered address of the applicant. Ranges between [−1, 429] months (-1 is a missing value).
  • customer_age (numeric): Applicant’s age in years, rounded to the decade. Ranges between [10, 90] years.
  • days_since_request (numeric): Number of days passed since application was done. Ranges between [0, 79] days.
  • intended_balcon_amount (numeric): Initial transferred amount for application. Ranges between [−16, 114] (negatives are missing values).
  • payment_type (categorical): Credit payment plan type. 5 possible (annonymized) values.
  • zip_count_4w (numeric): Number of applications within same zip code in last 4 weeks. Ranges between [1, 6830].
  • velocity_6h (numeric): Velocity of total applications made in last 6 hours i.e., average number of applications per hour in the last 6 hours. Ranges between [−175, 16818].
  • velocity_24h(numeric): Velocityoftotalapplicationsmadeinlast24hoursi.e.,average number of applications per hour in the last 24 hours. Ranges between [1297, 9586]
  • velocity_4w (numeric): Velocity of total applications made in last 4 weeks, i.e., average number of applications per hour in the last 4 weeks. Ranges between [2825, 7020].
  • bank_branch_count_8w (numeric): Number of total applications in the selected bank branch in last 8 weeks. Ranges between [0, 2404].
  • date_of_birth_distinct_emails_4w (numeric): Number of emails for applicants with same date of birth in last 4 weeks. Ranges between [0, 39].
  • employment_status (categorical): Employment status of the applicant. 7 possible (annonymized) values.
  • credit_risk_score (numeric): Internal score of application risk. Ranges between [−191, 389].
  • email_is_free (binary): Domain of application email (either free or paid).
  • housing_status (categorical): Current residential status for applicant. 7 possible (annonymized) values.
  • phone_home_valid (binary): Validity of provided home phone.
  • phone_mobile_valid (binary): Validity of provided mobile phone.
  • bank_months_count (numeric): How old is previous account (if held) in months. Ranges between [−1, 32] months (-1 is a missing value).
  • has_other_cards (binary): If applicant has other cards from the same banking com- pany.
  • proposed_credit_limit (numeric): Applicant’s proposed credit limit. Ranges between [200, 2000].
  • foreign_request (binary): If origin country of request is different from bank’s country. - source (categorical): Online source of application. Either browser (INTERNET) or app (TELEAPP).
  • session_length_in_minutes (numeric): Length of user session in banking website in minutes. Ranges between [−1, 107] minutes (-1 is a missing value).
  • device_os (categorical): Operative system of device that made request. Possible values are: Windows, macOS, Linux, X11, or other.
  • keep_alive_session (binary): User option on session logout.
  • device_distinct_emails (numeric): Number of distinct emails in banking website from the used device in last 8 weeks. Ranges between [−1, 2] emails (-1 is a missing value). - device_fraud_count (numeric): Number of fraudulent applications with used device. Ranges between [0, 1].
  • month (numeric): Month where the application was made. Ranges between [0, 7]. - fraud_bool (binary): If the application is fraudulent or not.

The csv named Based has been chosen to perform the analysis as is the real data set which has not been treated to bias and imbalance the variables for Machine Learning and model performance testing. The commands which(is.na(bankfraud_base)) and sum(is.na(bankfraud_base)) were applied to identify the position of the missing values and the count of them respectively. As a result, the file used does not contain missing values that have not been previously classified by the authors. From the dictionary, variables that contain \(-1\) and negative values have been specified by the authors as missing values. These missing value records have been filtered using the filter function from the dplyr library and stored in a new variable reducing the dimension of the data from \(1,000,000\) records to \(124,260\).

  theme_minimal() +

# Scatterplot of income vs fraud_bool
ggplot(bankfraud_base_nomissing, aes(x = income, y = fraud_bool)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "blue") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Income vs Fraud", x = "Income", y = "Fraud (0 = No, 1 = Yes)")

This graphic aids in determining whether income and the probability of fraud are related. For instance, it may indicate that income plays a role in fraud detection if the majority of fraudulent transactions (fraud_bool = 1) happen at a given income level. If points are dispersed equally among income levels, on the other hand, it would suggest that fraud is not highly predicted by income.

# Scatterplot of velocity_6h vs fraud_bool
ggplot(bankfraud_base_nomissing, aes(x = velocity_6h, y = fraud_bool)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "red") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Transaction Velocity (6h) vs Fraud", x = "Velocity (6h)", y = "Fraud (0 = No, 1 = Yes)")

This plot helps to visually explore whether there is a correlation between high transaction velocity and the likelihood of fraud. If fraudulent transactions (fraud_bool = 1) cluster at higher values of velocity_6h, it could indicate that high transaction velocity within a short time window is associated with a higher risk of fraud.

# Boxplot of income by fraud_bool
ggplot(bankfraud_base_nomissing, aes(x = factor(fraud_bool), y = income)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill = "green") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Income by Fraud", x = "Fraud (0 = No, 1 = Yes)", y = "Income")

he income distributions for fraudulent and non-fraudulent transactions can be compared with the aid of this graphic. Variations in the median or range of earnings may indicate a relationship between fraud risk and income.

In addition to possibly indicating whether greater or lower planned balances are associated with a higher risk of fraud, the plot aids in identifying any variations in intended balance amounts between fraud and non-fraud transactions.

5. Data Dimension Reduction

Sample Size: the total number of observations in the dataset is 124260 observations with 32 variables

Period: The Bank Account Fraud (BAF) suite of datasets has been published at NeurIPS 2022

Outcome Variable: The outcome we are predicting is fraud_bool, which indicates whether a transaction is fraudulent.

Predictor Variables: The remaining variables such as income, name_email_similarity, prev_address_months_count, customer_age, and others serve as predictors. There are few key predictors that are more likely to contribute to fraud detection they are credit_risk_score, device_fraud_count, foreign_request, etc.

Reason for reducing the dimensionality of the data: Increasing Model Efficiency: High-dimensional datasets have the potential to increase the computational cost and interpretive difficulty of models. Process optimization can be achieved by lowering the number of predictors. Minimizing Noise: Not every factor influences fraud prediction equally. In order to get rid of features that aren’t significant, dimensionality reduction helps. Certain variables may introduce noise or redundancy. Concentrating on Key Features: You can concentrate on the most important factors that genuinely help forecast fraud by lowering dimensionality.
